VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'World Agents and the researchers wanted to ask this question. Can regular image models actually understand 3D space even though they\'re just trained on 2D images? And the answer seems to be yes if you guide them correctly with agents.'

[17:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'So this is called World Agents and this is an agentic system that only uses an image model to build a full 3D world. So here\'s how it works. You would enter a text prompt describing the 3D scene you'

[17:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'want to generate and then it would go through this agentic loop. First, we have a director which well, directs everything. It looks at the current scene, it writes the next prompt and it decides what view to generate next. And'

[18:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'then we also have the generator which is in charge of actually rendering the scenes or the frames of the video. And then we have a verifier which actually checks if the new image fits the scene and if it doesn\'t, then it rejects it'

[18:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and it loops back to the director to generate a new scene. And then all the frames generated from this loop are then turned into 3D using Gaussian splatting as you can see here. And here are some of its generations. The initial prompt'

[18:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'describing the scene is below and as you can see, it\'s actually pretty good. You can move around in the 3D scene and it does remain consistent at all angles. So their project proves that indeed, we can just use a 2D image model to build 3D'

[18:39] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'worlds without any additional training required. You can just use existing diffusion models to potentially generate explorable 3D environments. Right now they\'ve only released a technical paper.'

