[38:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'page in the description below. Next up, this AI is quite fascinating. So, it\'s called Pulse of Motion, and this teaches AI to understand real-world timing. Not just how things look, but how fast they should move. Because if you look at'

[38:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these examples right now, even the best video models can generate smooth and realistic motion, but often the timing is wrong. Sometimes the movements feel too fast, or sometimes they\'re too slow, or just inconsistent. And that\'s because'

[38:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'these models don\'t actually understand real physical time. They\'re trained on tons of videos with different speeds, all normalized into the same frame rate, which creates what the researchers called chronometric hallucination,'

[39:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'meaning the model kind of guesses the timing instead of truly understanding it. So, here they created this AI to fix this. The idea is pretty simple. The model looks directly at the motion in'

[39:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the video and tries to recover the true physical frame rate. In other words, how fast the motion should actually happen in real life. Hopefully, you can see a noticeable difference after plugging it through this AI. The videos immediately'

[39:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'look a lot more realistic, and the timing looks a lot more correct. The nice thing is they\'ve released the code to this already. So, if you click on this button, and you scroll down a bit, here it contains all the instructions on'

[39:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'how to download and run this locally on your computer. Note that this is quite tiny at less than 2 GB in size. So, you should be able to run this on most consumer hardware. If you\'re interested in reading further, I\'ll link to this'

[39:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'main page in the description below. All right, next up we have this AI called mega flow. This is a model that figures out how every pixel in a video moves, even when the motion is huge or fast or chaotic. So, this task is called optical'

[40:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'flow, which means tracking how things move over time, and it\'s way harder than it sounds, especially when objects move far distances or when they change appearance. But, this AI is able to'

[40:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'handle this very well. It solves something called large displacement, which is when objects move a lot between different frames, like a fast car or a fast camera pan or something jumping across the screen. Other methods'

[40:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'struggle here because they rely on local search, meaning they only look at small areas and try to match things nearby. So, they\'re not able to handle these more chaotic movements. But, mega flow is able to capture these very well'

[40:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because it actually starts globally by matching points across the entire image first, so it can immediately connect where something is now to where it was, even if it moved far away. And then,'

[40:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'once it has a rough global match, it refines it step by step with a lightweight process to get even higher precision. So, this combination of global first and then local refinement is what makes it so effective. And if'

[41:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you compare this with other competitors, note that this new mega flow achieves state-of-the-art results in terms of pixel tracking accuracy. The awesome thing is, if you scroll up to the top of the page, they\'ve already released the'

[41:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'code to this. So, if you click on this GitHub repo, here it contains all the instructions on how to download and run this locally on your computer. Note that there are three models for various use cases, and each one is less than 4 GB in'

